## v1.10.0 (2026-07-03)

**Changed by:** Myrmidons issue #751 implementation session (canonical release check) â€” HomericIntelligence/Myrmidons issue #751 / branch `751-auto-impl`, executed 2026-07-03.
**Verification:** verified-local â€” full local gates passed (106/106 bats tests incl. 4 new, doc-drift 0 errors, actionlint clean on the new workflow, `just package` produced a 51-agent/6-fleet archive); CI pending on the Myrmidons PR at capture time, so NOT verified-ci. Frontmatter `verification` updated `unverified` â†’ `verified-local` (the skill's #1448 ghost-directory instance already established the verified-local precedent).

### What changed
- Added a new "Verified-local instance: canonical `release` check for a GitOps dataset repo (Myrmidons #751)" subsection inside the "Sub-Pattern: Canonical `install` Check for a Manifest/Dataset Repo" section, capturing eight EXECUTED lessons: (1) "don't fabricate the signal" confirmed for the `release` board cell â€” a real packaging script (`scripts/package-dataset.sh`) archiving `agents/`/`fleets/`/`schemas/` into `dist/myrmidons-dataset-<version>.tar.gz` with a `RELEASE_INFO` manifest (version, commit SHA, commit-date via `git log -1 --format=%cI` for per-commit determinism, agent/fleet counts), an empty-dataset exit-1 refusal, and stale-archive cleanup, instead of a no-op job emitting the check-run name; (2) SIGPIPE-safe archive verification â€” never `tar -tzf | grep -q` under `pipefail` (exit 141 flake); capture the listing once and grep herestrings; (3) least-privilege two-job split â€” canonical `release` job holds only `contents: read` on PR/main/tag triggers, a tag-gated `publish-release` job is the sole `contents: write` holder and RE-RUNS the deterministic packaging script rather than downloading the artifact; (4) `GITHUB_REF_NAME`-on-tags / `snapshot-<short-sha>` version derivation because `git describe` is unusable on shallow checkouts; (5) `PACKAGE_DATASET_ROOT` root-override env var so 4 bats cases (happy path, explicit version, empty-dataset negative, stale-archive re-run) drive `mktemp -d` git fixtures and ride the already-wired `pixi test-unit` gate â€” the one justified new workflow is the check-run itself; (6) verify third-party action pins against the tag before use (`gh api repos/actions/upload-artifact/git/ref/tags/v4.6.2 --jq '.object.sha'` matched `ea165f8d65b6e75b540449e92b4886f43607fa02`); (7) environmental lint-gap honesty â€” the system actionlint binary was absent locally, so the new workflow was linted directly with the pinned release binary in /tmp and the gap REPORTED, neither claimed green nor skipped; (8) doc sync across all homes (README badge row, CLAUDE.md CI/CD bullet, `docs/branch-protection.md` deliberate-omission note that `release` is intentionally NOT a required check because publishing is post-merge).
- Updated the sub-pattern's warning block to distinguish the still-plan-only #750 install material from the now verified-local #751 release instance.
- Extended the frontmatter description with trigger (11): adding a canonical `release`/packaging CI check-run for an ecosystem CI board to a manifest/dataset repo, where the check must do real packaging work rather than fabricate a pass, with a least-privilege tag-gated publish split and action-pin verification.
- Added a Verified On table row for Myrmidons #751 (`verified-local`).
- Added tags `canonical-check-run`, `release-packaging`, `least-privilege-workflow`, `sigpipe-safe`, `action-pin-verification`, `myrmidons` (frontmatter + footer). Bumped frontmatter version 1.9.0 â†’ 1.10.0 (MINOR â€” new verified-local instance + new trigger + new tags); date stays 2026-07-03; `verification` raised `unverified` â†’ `verified-local`.

### Why
This is the EXECUTED companion to the v1.9.0 plan-only #750 install sub-pattern: the same Odysseus ecosystem CI-naming rollout, now for the `release` board cell, taken end-to-end through implementation and full local gates in Myrmidons #751. It confirms the sub-pattern's central claim ("prefer a real check over a fabricated pass") with a shipped artifact, and contributes durable, transferable mechanisms â€” the SIGPIPE-safe tar-listing idiom, the least-privilege two-job release split with deterministic re-run instead of artifact download, shallow-checkout version derivation, the root-override fixture pattern for testing a tree-mutating script, tag-verified action pinning, and the environmental-lint-gap honesty rule â€” that apply to any future canonical release/packaging check in the ecosystem.

### Previous version (v1.9.0) snapshot

The full v1.9.0 skill file content prior to this amendment:
````markdown
---
name: architecture-executable-convention-guard-pattern
description: "Turn an un-guarded documented invariant (a prose convention) into a tested, blocking, reusable executable check that CI or any consumer can call. Use when: (1) a contract like 'absence of artifact X means stage Y never ran' lives only in docstrings/comments and nothing asserts it, (2) you are adding an enforcement gate whose whole purpose is signal fidelity and must pick a collision-free exit code distinct from argparse's usage-error 2 and sibling CLIs, (3) a verification step must resolve its inputs strictly read-only and must NOT fabricate the very signal whose absence it checks (e.g. a resolver that mkdir()s the directory), (4) you classify a log/marker line and must anchor on the line prefix instead of a free substring scan vulnerable to user-controlled tokens, (5) you relax argparse requirements (nargs='?') for a new mode and must re-guard the original mode so it does not silently no-op, (6) the same convention is documented in two places (module docstring + sibling shell comment) and must be kept in sync when made executable, (7) you are planning a fix for any 'X mirrors Y' / parity / directory-structure invariant audit finding and must determine WHICH direction(s) the existing guard asserts â€” the defect is usually the un-asserted reverse direction (test_packages - src_packages), and the fix is an allowlist-with-rationale plus the reverse check, NOT deletion of flagged items, (8) you are adding an executable membership/coverage guard that ITERATES a population (all packages / dirs / files of a kind) â€” you MUST scope its iteration set AND its CI/pre-commit files: trigger to the issue's NAMED targets only when sibling members are partially compliant, or the guard fails its OWN acceptance test on the shipped tree, (9) you are adding an install/package-consumability CI gate (cmake --install layout check + find_package consumer compile) for a library, or need a guard to exercise its own failure branches on every CI run via an always-on self-test against a mutated throwaway copy of its input, (10) a repo missing a canonical ecosystem CI check name (install/package/release) must choose between adding a REAL check vs documenting N/A â€” prefer a real check when the repo's documented quick-start install path IS an install surface (dependency-manager env + hook install), and verify the board's badge mechanism (check-runs on main) before picking the workflow/trigger."
